A former bank employee was charged in a Mombasa court with forging documents to get a Sh1.5 billion loan from the Kenya Commercial Bank. James Mwangi Muturi appeared before senior resident magistrate Martin Rabera on Thursday last week.He faces seven counts of forging documents of companies of the late Tahir Sheikh Said, famously known as TSS, to secure a loan. Muturi, said to be owning a chain of companies, denied the charges.He is alleged to have committed the offence on February 8 last year.Muturi was released on a Sh3 million bond with one surety. The magistrate directed that the case be mentioned on March 14.Under the Kenyan Penal Code, forgery is punishable by imprisonment, depending on severity.